That doesn't appear to be what's happening.  It just looks like the US
companies have overextended themselves a little bit.  Not only has that
created a supply/demand imbalance but it has driven up the license fees.
As a result of this, the market is going through a readjustment phase.

The Japanese are not translating and subbing their works.  They generally
rely on the foreign market to localize the properrties.  A good indication
of this is the practice of the Japanese anime satellite channel, Animax,
when operating in non-Japanese markets.  For example, the preponderence of
Animax's Southeast Asia and South Asia English language broadcasts rely
either on officially licensed English language versions or outsourcing the
localization to a company in the target market.

The point you raise about the Japanese offering anime for legal download
over the net is worth considering.  The Japanese are, in fact,
experimenting with delivery of TV and other media content over the
internet.  However, this is restricted to the Japanese market.  The most
ambitious undertaking, for example, is GyaO.  It's a broadcast model that
delivers a broad spectrum (including anime) of high quality internet video
on demand that you can watch on a PC or PC hooked to a TV through a device
provided by GyaO.  However, it's available only to Japanese IP addresses
and there are no immediate plans to expand to foreign markets.

The bottom line is that Funimation and ADV bit off a little more than they
could chew and now they have to adjust accordingly - at least, they don't
have quite the uphill battle facing Geneon and Bandai.  Significantly, many
of the Funimation layoffs were in the online area which would argue against
web-based delivery affecting DVD sales.  Even if, as you suggest, the
online impetus were to come from Japan, it would stand to reason that North
American companies would beef up in their online departments to assist in
the localization.  The evidence indicates that, although there have been
some small experiments, it'll be a while before we see a mature online
anime distribution business model in North America.
--

Phil
